Marshall syndrome is a rare genetic disorder (autosomal recessive) characterized by skeletal, skin, and reproductive abnormalities. Dermatologic findings include generalized thin, atrophic skin with **fine wrinkles**, which aligns with the patient's presentation. Although more commonly diagnosed in childhood, skin manifestations may persist or become evident later in adulthood. The patient’s demographics (age, race) and the absence of systemic features in the question do not rule out Marshall syndrome. Other options—Anetoderma (depigmented plaques), mid-dermal elastolysis (part of elastin-related syndromes but less specific), and perifollicular elastolysis (associated with elastosis or cystic changes)—are less consistent with the described clinical picture. Thus, Marshall syndrome remains the most likely diagnosis.

